{
  "promptTemplate": "({{movement}} {{material}} {{artisanal_vibes}} {{year}} (Rube Goldberg machine) with a gorgeous color palette of {{palette}})\n\n[An artistic and unique cross-sectional view of an ultra-maximalist style machine, drawing inspiration primarily from the impressive, intricate, and visually complex analog modular Rube Goldberg device. This bespoke creation is set in the bold futuristic timeline of {{year}}, and showcases a brilliantly unprecedented architectural design. Its aesthetic appeal is deeply rooted in, yet going beyond, mid-century Populuxe Googie architecture, effortlessly blending it with a hint of lo-fi pastel minimalism. The device's interactive elements represent a visually stimulating selection of materials. Notice the soft and lush needle-felted switches, the virtually tangible textures of gelatinous patch cables, and the familiar roughness of polyester knobs, all expertly incorporated within the unmissable charm of mid-century wood paneling. This seemingly complex blend of textures is made soothing through the choice of color palette that gracefully juxtaposes minimalist pastel hues of {{palette}} against an off-white backdrop. The entire artwork is cleverly positioned within a brightly lit mirrored room to increase the play of light and shadow and to boost its aesthetic appeal.] {{alt_prompt}} A film photograph of a wonky, Seussian living room transformed into an elaborate Rube Goldberg playground, where Fisher-Price, LEGO, and Playskool toys have been repurposed into an impossibly complex machine. The scene is meticulously composed yet delightfully chaotic, bathed in warm, slightly desaturated tones characteristic of 1970s photography. Along the walls, vintage mechanical figures operate massive gears made from Connect Four boards and K-nex, while rainbow-colored Hot Wheels tracks spiral through the space like roller coasters. The machine's heart features a towering geodesic dome constructed from Lite-Brite pegs, casting prismatic patterns across a {{color1}} shag carpet. Spiraling outward, Speak & Spell screens flicker in sequence, triggering elaborate chain reactions involving marbles rolling down Operation game boards. A refurbished 1980s desktop computer, decorated with Colorforms and Play-Doh sculptures, serves as both sculpture and functional component. The ceiling is a canopy of dangling connections sequenced to pass colorful balls through transparent tubes.",
